                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            {/* Lighthouse scores for pyxle.dev itself */}
            <section className="px-6 pb-20">
                <div className="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
                    <SectionHeading
                        label="Real-world"
                        title="pyxle.dev scores 100 on Lighthouse"
                        subtitle="This marketing site is a live Pyxle app — server-rendered on every request. Google's Lighthouse (desktop) rates it a perfect 100 across all four categories."
                    />
                    <LighthouseScoreCard />
                </div>
            </section>

            {/* SSR Comparison — first because SSR is Pyxle's core differentiator */}
            <section className="px-6 pb-20">
                <div className="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
                    <SectionHeading
                        label="Dynamic SSR"
                        title="Server-side rendering: faster than Next.js"
                        subtitle="The full page re-rendered on every request — the apples-to-apples match for Pyxle's @server loader and Next.js's force-dynamic. On byte-for-byte identical pages, Pyxle is faster at every complexity, and the gap grows as pages get heavier."
                    />
                    <div className={`rounded-xl border overflow-hidden border-zinc-200 dark:border-white/5`}>
                        <div className="overflow-x-auto">
                            <table className="w-full text-sm">
                                <thead>
                                    <tr className={'bg-zinc-50 dark:bg-white/[0.03]'}>
                                        <th className="px-5 py-3 text-left font-semibold">Page rendered per request</th>
                                        <th className="px-5 py-3 text-right font-semibold text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400">Pyxle (req/s)</th>
                                        <th className="px-5 py-3 text-right font-semibold">Next.js (req/s)</th>
                                        <th className="px-5 py-3 text-right font-semibold">Pyxle advantage</th>
                                    </tr>
                                </thead>
                                <tbody>
                                    {SSR_COMPARISON.map((row) => {
                                        const ratio = (row.pyxle / row.nextjs).toFixed(2);
                                        return (
                                            <tr key={row.page} className={`border-t border-zinc-100 dark:border-white/5`}>
                                                <td className="px-5 py-3 align-top">
                                                    <span className="font-medium">{row.page}</span>
                                                    <span className="block text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400 mt-0.5">{row.detail}</span>
                                                </td>
                                                <td className="px-5 py-3 text-right font-mono text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400 font-medium align-top">{row.pyxle.toLocaleString()}</td>
                                                <td className={`px-5 py-3 text-right font-mono text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400 align-top`}>{row.nextjs.toLocaleString()}</td>
                                                <td className={`px-5 py-3 text-right font-mono font-semibold text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400 align-top`}>{ratio}×</td>
                                            </tr>
                                        );
                                    })}
                                </tbody>
                            </table>
                        </div>
                        <div className={`px-5 py-3 text-xs border-t border-zinc-100 text-zinc-600 dark:border-white/5 dark:text-zinc-400`}>
                            At 50 concurrent connections; the advantage holds across 1–100 connections (1.25–2.1×). Both frameworks render React on the server with full HTML document assembly — Pyxle via a persistent Node.js worker pool, Next.js via React Server Components.
                            {' '}<strong>The fair caveat:</strong> this measures pages that <em>must</em> render per request (personalized, authenticated, real-time). For static or cacheable content, Next.js pre-renders to HTML and serves it at static-file speed.
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            {/* API Benchmarks */}
            <section className="px-6 pb-20">
                <div className="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
                    <div className="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-end sm:justify-between mb-10 gap-4">
